<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n36126h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36126h">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36126h"> 126(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Tovi the Proud</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The earliest title-deed we possess is a twelfth-century manuscript &hellip; written by one of the canons of Waltham, and tells how <mark>Tovi the Proud</mark>, Staller and Standard Bearer of King Canute, being enraptured at the discovery of the Holy Cross upon his Somerset estate and at the miracles that attended its removal to Waltham, took off his splendid raiment, clothed himself in sackcloth, and with humbled voice and heart and many tears pronounced this adoration and these vows: &ldquo;&hellip; I devote and dedicate to Thee myself, and I give for ever whatever property I have in any way acquired, to wit: Waltham, Kelvedon, <i>Hicce</i> (iii), Lambeth, Loughton and Alvertun, for the support of all those who shall serve Thee.&rdquo; <small> Reginald L. Hine, <a name="RLHH" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RLHH"><cite title="source">The History of Hitchin</cite></a>, Vol. I. (Nov 1929) 25</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: IX.A.2-1: &ldquo;De inventione Sanctas Crucis nostras in Monte Aoute et de ductione ejusdem apud Waltham (the earliest tile deed) &ldquo;Tovi the Proud, Staller and Standard Bearer of King Canute&rdquo; </mm> </dd></dl>
